			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Fatal Bard Kite in Dulak<a name="50954"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jul 9 04 1:20 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span><blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">my point is, bards can do stupid things too. it goes both ways.</span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
Hence my statement:
<br />

<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">Yes bards (and other kiters) need to be considerate of groups in the area by keeping their kite under control (doesn't count stupid people screwing with your kite) and not monopolizing the entire zone. However, bards do not need to pack up and leave just because another person is in the zone with them.</span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
Mistakes happen to everyone.  Accidents happen and are excusable.  
<br />

<br />
A bard dying just as a group pulls close to it is an accident.  Someone healing a bard to be nice and accidentally drawing agro of the whole kite is an accident (the first time anyhow).
<br />

<br />
Someone trying to pull out of someone's kite and getting agro isn't an accident though.  The bard running a kite near a group and fading isn't an accident.  
<br />

<br />
Some people are good-natured, some aren't.  Most of the time people are truly only trying to help.  If they were really just trying to help, I do my best to explain how bard kites work and life goes on.  If they do it intentionally or out of spit, things can get ugly.  
<br />

<br />
For example, I was helping with a CR in Fear last weekend.  I broke into the zone and started my chant kiting (different run speeds of mobs make ae'ing a bad idea typically).  There was a necro and monk that had managed to FD and didn't die with the rest of the folks.  The necro kept trying to stand up, dot, charm, and other stuff.  Everytime he would, a portion of the  kite would rush to him.  When he would FD again and the kite would rush back to me, usually from the opposite side of my kite.  I finally got him to stay down and quit messing with my ktie.  Afterwards I was able to explain to him that bards have zero agro on their kites and controlling where the mobs were is key to keeping alive (i.e. mobs charging me from the opposite side of where the rest of the mobs are is a bad thing).  He had no clue since the necro usually has a ton of agro when they kite.  Live and learn and educate.  </span></td>
			</tr><tr>
